<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-08-31T20:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-08-31T20:00:00-05:00" n="404" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d404">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 P. W./9–145: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Hurley</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-09-01T08:00:00+07:00">September 1,
                                1945—8 a.m.</date>
                            <lb/> [Received September 1—2:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>1492. The following message is from Generalissimo Chiang Kai-shek for
                        President Truman.</p>
                    <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“The United States Fleet and United States Forces are welcome at any port
                            in China. The British Fleet and British Forces and other imperialist
                            forces are not welcome in China. I respectfully request that if and when
                            the American Fleet enters any China port it will not be accompanied by
                            any British ships or contingent.”</p>
                    </quote>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hurley</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>